text: Stopping by the LMA mid-winter conference to give a federal update. https://t.co/CqUqLrZrPa
Project efficiency is not limited to highways. The West Shore flood control project was in the STUDY phase for 42 years before proposed for construction.  And construction still hasn't started.
The fact that we call the Mississippi River bridge that was built before I was born as "new" is the best indicator that something needs to change.
There is no doubt we need more money to support infrastructure in the capital region but we can't keep spending money in the same system that got us to this point.
Brand new four lane roads in areas that don't have traffic don't make sense when there isn't enough investment in the capital region - some of the worst traffic in the US.
The current infrastructure prioritization system in place today is flawed. Project development needs to be metric based and objective.
We don't have years of infrastructure investment to catch up on. We have decades.
Tax reform - not just important for take home pay, but also making the US more competitive in the international marketplace. https://t.co/i1w79Lg5mS
We're changing the game. For every one regulation, we're cutting two. While we're changing the game and setting conditions for success, we have to ensure our workforce is prepared to compete.
More investments are returning home. Like Apple bringing home $350 billion to invest in US and Spillway Sportsman expanding services, giving higher wages to employees and increasing jobs.  #TaxReform

text: Check out my website for more information: https://t.co/1AHLruvfTL
This is the way that government is supposed to work. #DRRA
It truly captures and takes action on the frontline feedback and lessons learned from our August flood, recent hurricanes, and other events.
This is one of the most significant disaster recovery and preparedness bills in decades. #DRRA
We pushed hard for the H.R. 4460 provision that qualifies houses of worship and faith-based non-profits for FEMA assistance to repair, restore or replace when they are damaged.
Without fail, some of the most reliable, generous agents of recovery are the many churches in the Capital Region.
This policy will help to make the necessary changes to the interstate barrier and drainage to facilitate evacuations and road usage during floods. #DRRA
Like I-12 in Baton Rouge and Livingston Parish.
H.R. 4460 requires FEMA to collaborate with the Federal Highway Administration to develop policy on the design, construction and repair of evacuations routes‚Ä¶
This will alleviate much of the headache that many Louisianans experienced during last year‚Äôs flood.

The DRRA requires FEMA and other agencies work to implement a streamlined process whereby disaster victims can provide information one time to a federal agency rather than having to apply multiple times to multiple agencies for disaster assistance.
Ultimately saving taxpayer dollars.  The bill also funds a ‚Äúsurge‚Äù of building inspectors to help address permitting and assessment activities that typically delay rebuilding and recovery.
The DRRA establishes a new program where rebuilding and recovery efforts can include resilient construction to help prevent repetitive losses and to prepare for future disasters‚Ä¶
The amendment also makes food banks eligible for FEMA repair assistance.

T&I unanimously adopted our amendment requiring FEMA to more closely collaborate with food banks like the Greater Baton Rouge Area Food Bank, St. Vincent de Paul, and Long-term Recovery Groups like Rebuild Louisiana, Samaritan‚Äôs Purse, and others.
It‚Äôs important to invest federal dollars in projects that will prevent these disasters from happening in the future.
Like the Comite River Diversion Canal. #DRRA
Our amendment also clarifies the flexibility to states and local governments to complete MUCH needed flood mitigation projects‚Ä¶
For example, the DRRA will eliminate the very flawed ‚Äúduplication of benefits‚Äù policy that prevents LA flood survivors from gaining Restore LA grants.
Several of mine and Congressman Richmond‚Äôs policies were included in the bill‚Ä¶

The DRRA represents an important move toward the federal government taking a more proactive approach to disaster preparation, relief and recovery which is something that I have advocated for a long time.
Can better prepare for, respond to, recover from, and mitigate against floods, hurricanes and disasters of all kinds. #DRRA
And It cuts through bureaucracies when disaster strikes so that families, individuals, small businesses, and state and local governments‚Ä¶
This bill makes critical reforms to FEMA‚Äôs disaster response and recovery programs to provide on the ground help‚Ä¶
Yesterday The Disaster Recovery Reform Act was unanimously approved by the Transportation and Infrastructure committee. #DRRA

text: Approaching one year later from the flood and no one has touched the walls, no drainage outlets, nothing.
We asked the Fed. Highway Admin to update us on safety standards and timeline to fixing these problems so this doesn't happen again.
We beg for levees like this in south Louisiana but to have one on the interstate is crazy.
There are many safety aspects w/ interstate walls, but why do fed standards not call for certain amt. of drainage flow or offsetting walls?
The I-12 wall exacerbated the flooding, it goes on for miles & there are no drainage features.
During the FAST act hearing, I addressed the Fed. Highway Admin and showed them pictures of I-12 flooding in Walker from last Aug. flood. https://t.co/xGieyTvNBa

This has nothing to do with politics; it is just frustrating and sloppy

program.
Also challenges efforts in Congress to provide addt'l flood relief $ when not a penny of Sept. funding has been allocated to flood victims.
Impossible to explain to flood victims why $1.6B in recovery $ is stuck in bureaucracy while homes remain gutted, moldy and un-insulated.

This will further delay the allocation of badly-needed flood relief funds that we
appropriated in September.
Disappointed to hear that @RestoreLA_gov are restarting the flood relief contract solicitation.

Comite should have been completed decades ago, but now we actually have the opportunity to do it.
‚Ä¶ Few can afford the cost of raising their homes ‚Äì I know our family couldn‚Äôt afford it.
Completing it would also lower the region‚Äôs base flood elevation & eliminate need for many home/biz owners from having to raise their homes
With these Hazard Mitigation Grant Program funds, the state just has to prioritize the goals of the Comite project and move forward.
Through funds appropriated by Congress, Louisiana has more than $250 million in available flood and disaster prevention funds.
The project could be completed in approximately two years ‚Äì and the state has the federal funds available now to build it. @SteveRHardy

but we are committed to helping lead the trans-formative change.

Modernizing our country's  infrastructure starts with regulatory reform; You can‚Äôt do infrastructure without reg reform first.

text: We can achieve real environmental benefits through efforts compatible with economic growth.
We have to untangle our job creators from the costly burden of excessive regulations so they can prosper.
PROVE IT will bring fairness, transparency and accountability to the federal regulatory system.
but the over regulated public is still unfairly forced to pay for them.  We need to end this regulatory abuse.
The costs of regulations almost always exceed the self-serving predictions agencies use when the rules are issued,
The PROVE IT amendment requires federal agencies to regularly quantify and assess the regulations.
Billions of dollars that our biz and manufacturers could use to boost wages and grow jobs are diverted to comply with the new regulations.
Regulations are effectively a hidden tax.
Last week the House voted to approve the Regulatory Accountability Act with my PROVE IT amendment attached.
The top two most burdensome areas of regulation for small business were the federal tax code and Affordable Care Act. We can do better.
Because of the high costs of complying with regulations, more than half of small businesses have held off on hiring new employees.
According to the National Small Business Association, the average small-biz owner is spending at least $12k every year for regulations.
This has a significant impact on Louisiana‚Äôs jobs and economy.
Did you know that in Louisiana we have 74% more regulations than the rest of the country?
Yesterday I caught up with Bill and Kevin on @Talk107.3 and discussed the high cost of regulatory compliance https://t.co/TEb33Hxvx7

text: It‚Äôs time for tax code reform that is fairer, flatter, and simpler.
Doing your taxes shouldn‚Äôt be complicated.
We need a simpler, fairer tax code along with a simpler, fairer IRS.
Tax code reform should create a service-first IRS.
It should make it easier to create jobs, raise wages, and expand opportunity for all Americans‚Ä¶
A new tax code should not only make it easier to do your taxes, but also give you peace of mind.
We must make simplicity and fairness high priority with tax code reform.
We must offer a way to dramatic reform without increasing the deficit.
We can‚Äôt have a better tax code if we don‚Äôt have an IRS that puts taxpayers first.
It should make America the greatest place in the world to hire and invest.
Our tax code should be fair and simple for everyone‚Ä¶
To put it plainly, we need a new tax code.
The IRS has consistently violated the trust of the American taxpayer.
Our tax code isn‚Äôt promoting growth.  In fact, it‚Äôs pushing jobs overseas.
Every year it takes more just to do your taxes than pay them‚Ä¶ It‚Äôs unacceptable.
It‚Äôs made up of high rates, special interest breaks, and regulations that are too complicated to even understand‚Ä¶
Bottom line, our tax code is a mess.
The tax code and the IRS should work for ‚Äì not against ‚Äì the American people.
I support fundamental tax reform and believe it‚Äôs critical to restoring America‚Äôs competiveness.
